orman origin): probably a nickname for a quarrelsome person, from Old French <i>barat</i>, Middle English <i>bar(r)at</i>, <i>bar(r)et(te)</i> ‘trouble, distress’, later ‘deception, fraud; contention, strife’. Through Norman settlement it also became common in Ireland, where it was Gaelicized as <b>Baróid</b> (Munster) and <b>Baréid</b> (Connacht)."]},{"name":"Baret","meanings":["French:","derivative of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baro</i>, from <i>ber(o)</i> ‘bear’.","variant of   Barret   2. Compare   Barrette  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Simon Barret was born about 1359, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married Simon Barret in 1383, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1359–":"umbes 1359–Surnud","1359–Male":"1359–Surnud","1385–1456":"1385–1456","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1359":"1359","1456":"1456","Abt 1359":"umbes 1359","1385":"1385","1383":"1383","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hardwicke Manor, Norfolk, England":"Hardwicke, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hardwicke, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1359–":"noin 1359–Kuollut